 to the ways in which women are defined in relation to their genitals as patriarchal property and space and are valued according to reproduction as their primary labour. Erotic dance as it takes shape in the modern representation of Salome insists both that the mother is and is not visible in the body of the dancer, a contradiction this study characterizes as reproductive fetishism. Looking at a range of media, the study traces the modern figure of Salome through visual art, writing, early psychoanalysis and dance, from "hootchie kootch" to the performances dancer Maud Allan called “mimeo-dramatic” to mid-20th-century North American films such as Billy Wilder's Sunset Boulevard and Charles Lamont's Salome, Where She Danced to the 21st-century HBO series The Sopranos.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aDancezEuropexHistoryy19th century. 0aSex in dancezEuropexHistoryy19th century. 0aWomen dancerszEuropexHistoryy19th century. 7aPERFORMING ARTS / Dance / History & Criticism.2bisacsh  a"Little Egypt".  aLoie Fuller.  aMaud Allan.  aSalomania.  aSalome dancers.  acolonialism.  acooch dancers.  aerotic dance.  afemininity.  afetishism.  agender and early psychoanalysis.  ahootchie kootch.  aimages.  aimperial culture.  aintermediality.  amaternalism.  arace.  arepresentation.  areproduction.  awhiteness.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023z978311127195808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP w/o University of Toronto Press 2023 eBook Packagez978311143542840uhttps://doi.org/10.51644/978177112589540uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781771125895423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781771125895/original  a978-3-11-127195-8  ACUP Complete eBook-Package 2023b2023  a978-3-11-143542-8  ACUP 